snippet.textDisplay:
The solution to an overwhelmed medical system is to put together fleets of mobile treatment units.
Say a box van with supplies, a Dr., a nurse, followed by another box van "disinfection" unit.
The medical unit provides monitoring and treatment, and the disinfection unit monitors and addresses the safety of the medial staff and surrounding public.
These travel to the homes of "self quarantined" patients, monitoring them and administering treatment as required. Critical cases are transported to a medical center as required.
A major city might equip 1000 trucks on "routes" to the infected....where they make many stops each.
Unlike building new hospitals, this is scaleable, and provides ,much better protection against cross infection to the general population.
I think this is the only way to minimize the damage if the virus starts yielding 10's of thousands of cases in a country like the USA, otherwise nobody with regular flu symptoms will risk going to the hospital (or reporting).
This approach also keeps people from traveling when they suspect they've become ill, or waiting in contaminated hospitals that are already over-run.
It is also faster and likely cheaper than setting up temporary hospitals which may eventually be overwhelmed as well.
Just rent 1000 small box trucks, and shelving, and compartmentalize the affected in-place.
